40:20.334 --> 40:20.709
Donna Martin graduates!

40:20.793 --> 40:23.462
(gavel banging)

40:23.546 --> 40:26.882
This meeting will come back
to order.

40:26.966 --> 40:28.467
Donna Martin graduates!

40:28.551 --> 40:29.093
Donna Martin
graduates!

40:30.761 --> 40:33.681
Superintendent Ephardt.

40:33.764 --> 40:36.725
You're out of order,
Mr. Walsh.

40:36.809 --> 40:38.561
{\an6}I think we've gone
a little beyond Robert's
Rules at this point, George.

40:38.644 --> 40:40.688
{\an3}I'd like to hear what
Brandon has to say.

40:40.771 --> 40:44.024
(bystaThank you.eing)

40:44.108 --> 40:46.360
{\an3}Now, the students have
taken your "threats"

40:46.443 --> 40:49.363
{\an1}very seriously,
Superintendent Ephardt,

40:49.446 --> 40:51.323
{\an1}but I think you can judge
by their reaction

40:51.407 --> 40:52.867
{\an1}that no one's going
anywhere,

40:52.950 --> 40:53.534
{\an1}so unless you're prepared
to call the police

40:53.617 --> 40:56.203
to make us all go home,

40:56.287 --> 40:58.205
{\an3}I think you ought to
take what we're saying

40:58.289 --> 40:59.206
{\an3}a little more
seriously.

40:59.290 --> 41:01.375
{\an1}GIRL:
Yeah.

41:01.458 --> 41:04.712
{\an3}Now we're all here because
we believe in something.

41:04.795 --> 41:06.547
{\an3}You all would have
been very happy

41:06.630 --> 41:08.549
if you hadn't
caught someone

41:08.632 --> 41:11.051
{\an3}with an unblemished
school record,

41:11.135 --> 41:11.719
someone that you could
have very easily made

41:11.802 --> 41:13.596
an example out of.

41:13.679 --> 41:18.392
{\an3}That's what this rule
was all about, wasn't it?

41:18.475 --> 41:22.396
{\an3}However, ladies and gentlemen,
you caught the wrong person.

41:22.480 --> 41:25.024
You caught someone that doesn't
deserve to be treated like this.

41:25.107 --> 41:26.358
You caught our friend,

41:26.442 --> 41:27.568
Donna Martin.

41:27.651 --> 41:30.404
{\an3}Donna Martin is the
kind of girl that goes

41:30.487 --> 41:31.697
{\an1}out of her way
for people.

41:31.780 --> 41:33.407
{\an1}That's why all these people
here are going

41:33.490 --> 41:34.700
{\an1}out of their way
for her.

41:35.659 --> 41:38.245
We love Donna,

41:38.329 --> 41:40.122
{\an3}and we're not going
to see her hurt.

41:40.206 --> 41:41.373
(people applauding)

41:41.457 --> 41:43.500
Right on.

41:48.464 --> 41:50.466
{\an1}Thank you,
Mr. Walsh.

41:50.549 --> 41:52.718
(girl clears throat)

41:52.801 --> 41:54.345
Oh, one more thing.

41:54.428 --> 41:55.095
I don't think
you're going

41:55.179 --> 41:57.389
{\an1}to have much success
matriculating

41:57.473 --> 41:59.141
the juniors unless, uh,

41:59.225 --> 42:00.726
{\an1}you drop this whole
dress code thing.

42:00.809 --> 42:02.394
(people cheering)

42:03.520 --> 42:06.941
We'll take that
under advisement.

42:07.024 --> 42:07.942
Any questions?

42:08.025 --> 42:09.276
{\an3}Yeah.

42:09.360 --> 42:13.447
{\an3}I'd just like to say that
I, for one, am not prepared

42:13.530 --> 42:16.116
{\an3}to call the
police here today.

42:16.200 --> 42:18.577
{\an3}Therefore, I move we vote
to allow Donna Martin

42:18.661 --> 42:20.663
to graduate, provided
she enroll in a drug

42:20.746 --> 42:24.625
{\an3}and alcohol counseling
program at the Maple Center.

42:24.708 --> 42:26.585
Second.

42:26.669 --> 42:29.421
{\an3}I also suggest that we review
the dress code situation,

42:29.505 --> 42:30.464
{\an3}or we're going to
have a demonstration

42:30.547 --> 42:32.967
like this the first week
of school in September.

42:33.050 --> 42:34.510
That's right.

42:36.887 --> 42:39.807
Very well.

42:39.890 --> 42:43.811
{\an3}An aye vote signifies
Miss Martin will graduate.

42:43.894 --> 42:47.481
{\an3}A nay vote signifies
the decision

42:47.564 --> 42:48.983
{\an3}of the disciplinary
committee

42:49.066 --> 42:50.484
will stand.

42:51.777 --> 42:52.695
Mr. Chang.

42:52.778 --> 42:53.988
{\an1}Nay.

42:54.071 --> 42:55.322
{\an3}EPHARDT:
Mrs. Richter.

42:55.406 --> 42:56.073
Aye.

42:59.243 --> 43:00.327
Ms. Silverman?

43:00.411 --> 43:01.578
Aye.

43:03.163 --> 43:04.999
Mr. Pula?

43:05.082 --> 43:06.125
{\an3}Nay.

43:08.085 --> 43:12.423
{\an1}Mrs. Lufrano
for the final deciding vote.

43:18.095 --> 43:18.679
Aye.

43:18.762 --> 43:20.306
(cheering)

43:23.434 --> 43:26.395
{\an3}Thank God.

43:26.478 --> 43:26.812
Congratulations.

43:29.815 --> 43:31.734
(sighs)

43:31.817 --> 43:33.986
Congratulations.

43:34.069 --> 43:35.571
STEVE:
All right, I got a great idea.

43:35.654 --> 43:37.197
Let's all get drunk.

43:37.281 --> 43:40.367
(cheering)

43:40.451 --> 43:42.870
Steven,
I know I didn't hear that.

43:42.953 --> 43:44.580
Okay, everybody, fun's over.

43:44.663 --> 43:45.581
Let's go back to school.

43:45.664 --> 43:47.708
Afternoon finals will proceed
as scheduled.

43:47.791 --> 43:50.753
(all groaning)

43:50.836 --> 43:52.087
You, too, Donna.

43:52.171 --> 43:53.881
You know, Mrs. T.,
I have never been so happy

43:53.964 --> 43:55.883
to take a final
in my entire life.

44:00.804 --> 44:04.808
Congratulations, my sweetheart,
and welcome back.

44:04.892 --> 44:05.893
And in honor of Donna,

44:05.976 --> 44:09.605
a piece of pie of your choice
is on you know who.

44:09.688 --> 44:10.606
(laughs)

44:10.689 --> 44:12.900
Thank you, Nat.

44:12.983 --> 44:13.942
{\an3}(grunting):
The man of the hour.

44:14.026 --> 44:16.779
{\an1}Hail to the
conquering hero.

44:16.862 --> 44:19.281
Donna, I, uh,
I got a little present for you.

44:19.365 --> 44:21.408
Just open it.

44:21.492 --> 44:23.077
{\an1}It's something you worked
long and hard for.

44:23.160 --> 44:24.453
Okay.

44:26.372 --> 44:29.041
Oh...

44:29.124 --> 44:30.084
Thanks, guys.

44:30.167 --> 44:33.921
No one could ever,
ever have friends like you guys.

44:34.004 --> 44:36.131
♪♪

44:36.215 --> 44:39.385
Ladies and gentlemen,
I give you...

44:39.468 --> 44:41.095
the graduate.

44:41.178 --> 44:42.096
Whoo!

44:42.179 --> 44:43.263
{\an3}Ha, ha!

44:47.226 --> 44:48.977
♪♪

